1
00:00:04,957 --> 00:00:07,510
Welcome to the course
on Plasma Physics and Applications.

2
00:00:07,568 --> 00:00:10,028
Today we will discuss the regime
that we refer to as

3
00:00:10,028 --> 00:00:13,182
the <i>Burning Plasma Regime</i>
and the role of fast ions in it.

4
00:00:14,025 --> 00:00:17,215
We will start by defining 
what a burning plasma is

5
00:00:17,215 --> 00:00:20,119
and by highlighting its specificities.

6
00:00:20,229 --> 00:00:24,563
We will describe the fast ions 
and their role in the external

7
00:00:24,563 --> 00:00:26,458
and the self-heating of the plasma.

8
00:00:26,756 --> 00:00:29,941
We will then look at the losses
that fast ions can be subject to

9
00:00:29,941 --> 00:00:31,896
because of a number of reasons:

10
00:00:31,896 --> 00:00:33,623
- inhomogeneities in the field,

11
00:00:33,708 --> 00:00:36,258
- low frequency plasma modes,

12
00:00:36,588 --> 00:00:37,673
- turbulence,

13
00:00:37,673 --> 00:00:40,106
- or resonant interaction with Alfvén waves.

14
00:00:40,509 --> 00:00:42,921
We’ll then say a few words
about the stability of the burn

15
00:00:42,921 --> 00:00:44,543
and its control.

16
00:00:45,233 --> 00:00:47,621
I would like to start 
by reminding ourselves

17
00:00:47,621 --> 00:00:49,478
about the DT fusion reaction.

18
00:00:49,478 --> 00:00:53,370
The one we’ll use for ITER
and the first generation of reactors.

19
00:00:54,346 --> 00:00:58,699
As we have said already together
we have a tritium and a deuterium ion

20
00:00:58,699 --> 00:01:03,500
that fuse, producing a neutron,
at 14 MeV of energy

21
00:01:03,500 --> 00:01:07,040
and a helium nucleus
at 3.5 MeV of energy;

22
00:01:07,040 --> 00:01:08,944
that’s an alpha particle [α-particle]

23
00:01:09,040 --> 00:01:10,725
The neutron has two jobs:

24
00:01:10,725 --> 00:01:14,553
it will react to the lithium 6 
that would be present in the blanket

25
00:01:14,553 --> 00:01:18,948
to produce the tritium
that we need for the reactions themselves,

26
00:01:19,233 --> 00:01:23,938
and of course it will be used
to heat a fluid around the plasma

27
00:01:23,938 --> 00:01:26,344
that will be used to generate electricity.

28
00:01:28,646 --> 00:01:32,662
The α-particle has 
one single task for us

29
00:01:32,662 --> 00:01:33,749
which is very important.

30
00:01:33,749 --> 00:01:39,025
It has to be kept in a plasma 
and heat the plasma ions in the core

31
00:01:39,083 --> 00:01:41,310
so that they maintain reactivity.

32
00:01:41,421 --> 00:01:43,632
We call that the plasma self-heating.

33
00:01:43,844 --> 00:01:45,758
So what is a burning plasma?

34
00:01:45,758 --> 00:01:47,430
Let’s recall the energy balance.

35
00:01:47,430 --> 00:01:51,940
We have a possible variation
of the energy contained in a plasma

36
00:01:51,940 --> 00:01:56,514
because the α-particles heat it,
if we have fusion reactions,

37
00:01:56,514 --> 00:01:59,193
or because we put power from the outside,

38
00:01:59,193 --> 00:02:02,193
the so-called additional or external heating.

39
00:02:02,193 --> 00:02:04,476
And of course with the minus sign

40
00:02:04,476 --> 00:02:07,502
we have to include the term for the losses

41
00:02:07,502 --> 00:02:10,360
that we have said in the past 
being dominating in general

42
00:02:10,360 --> 00:02:11,735
by direct losses,

43
00:02:11,806 --> 00:02:15,673
represented by a single parameter
which is the energy confinement time.

44
00:02:17,250 --> 00:02:20,688
Let’s express 
the fusion energy gain Q.

45
00:02:20,688 --> 00:02:23,626
That’s the fusion power
divided by the input power,

46
00:02:23,676 --> 00:02:28,007
and because the α-power
is about one-fifth of the total,

47
00:02:28,007 --> 00:02:33,246
we can write - that’s about 
five times the power

48
00:02:33,246 --> 00:02:36,406
in the α-particles
divided by the input power.

49
00:02:37,531 --> 00:02:40,168
So if we are interested
in the heating fraction

50
00:02:40,168 --> 00:02:43,980
that comes from the α's, 
the α-heating fraction, fα

51
00:02:44,210 --> 00:02:48,606
which is the power in the α's
divided by total power,

52
00:02:48,697 --> 00:02:54,422
that can be presented in terms of
a very simple expression containing Q.

53
00:02:54,422 --> 00:02:56,226
That’s Q / (Q + 5).

54
00:02:57,197 --> 00:03:00,057
So the experiments
we have performed so far

55
00:03:00,095 --> 00:03:04,663
have reached a Q of less than,
say about 0.7,

56
00:03:04,663 --> 00:03:08,043
which corresponds to an 
α-heating fraction of less than 12%.

57
00:03:08,482 --> 00:03:11,798
So really the α-heating term
is sub-dominant

58
00:03:11,798 --> 00:03:15,231
compared to what we heat the plasma
with from outside.

59
00:03:15,778 --> 00:03:19,220
Even here if we had reached <i>breakeven</i>
which corresponds to Q=1,

60
00:03:19,318 --> 00:03:22,824
the α-heating fraction
would be only about 17%.

61
00:03:23,708 --> 00:03:28,768
So the limit at which we start
to have a different regime is Q=5,

62
00:03:28,768 --> 00:03:33,839
because at Q=5 we have an 
α-heating fraction of 50%.

63
00:03:34,489 --> 00:03:42,911
So what goes on starting from that value 
of Q, to higher and higher values of Q’s ?

64
00:03:42,921 --> 00:03:46,535
It is what we call the 
burning plasma regime.

65
00:03:46,793 --> 00:03:51,910
This is the burning plasma regime
because the plasma in a sense

66
00:03:51,910 --> 00:03:56,523
is a dominated in its heating 
by its own by-products.

67
00:03:56,523 --> 00:03:59,625
Of course the limit is exactly Q=5
but if you have Q=10

68
00:03:59,625 --> 00:04:03,607
then we have an α-heating fraction
which is about 67%

69
00:04:03,607 --> 00:04:08,018
and going all the way to 100%
when we reach ignition

70
00:04:08,018 --> 00:04:11,595
at which point of course 
the gain goes to infinity.

71
00:04:12,575 --> 00:04:15,646
We don’t have burning
plasmas as of today.

72
00:04:16,273 --> 00:04:20,589
So we can only speculate
on what their specificities will be.

73
00:04:20,991 --> 00:04:23,386
First of all, we need to reach
high performance,

74
00:04:23,386 --> 00:04:25,639
so burning plasma would be, 
sort of by definition,

75
00:04:25,639 --> 00:04:29,694
high-performance plasma
in a tokamak reactor.

76
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:33,219
It will be close to the operational limits
that we can have.

77
00:04:33,386 --> 00:04:37,304
It will have very large heat flux
on the plasma facing components,

78
00:04:37,304 --> 00:04:39,709
as large as you can cope with generally.

79
00:04:39,887 --> 00:04:43,290
It would be a nuclear environment, 
something we don’t have, again, today.

80
00:04:43,559 --> 00:04:45,743
There will be 
a lot of radiation involved,

81
00:04:45,872 --> 00:04:49,242
there will be the issue 
of the retention of tritium,

82
00:04:49,242 --> 00:04:53,339
for example
in the first wall of the tokamak,

83
00:04:53,339 --> 00:04:56,029
there will be the issue of dust production
that contains tritium,

84
00:04:56,029 --> 00:05:00,133
there will be the issue of course 
of the need for breeding the tritium

85
00:05:00,133 --> 00:05:03,974
using the blanket modules
outside the plasma.

86
00:05:04,294 --> 00:05:08,037
In terms of the plasma
physics specificities,

87
00:05:08,173 --> 00:05:12,761
also, we expect something 
different from today, for a few reasons.

88
00:05:12,761 --> 00:05:16,751
First of all, it will be at
very high density and temperature

89
00:05:16,751 --> 00:05:19,560
compared to what we have today,

90
00:05:19,657 --> 00:05:21,778
which implies we are in a regime

91
00:05:21,778 --> 00:05:24,762
where we have even lower 
and lower collisionality

92
00:05:24,762 --> 00:05:28,282
compared to what we have today 
in present devices

93
00:05:28,282 --> 00:05:32,517
and perhaps even more importantly
in terms of basic physics,

94
00:05:32,517 --> 00:05:34,517
we have a very small ratio

95
00:05:34,517 --> 00:05:39,762
between the size
of the plasma particle orbit

96
00:05:39,762 --> 00:05:41,589
and the size of the device.

97
00:05:41,914 --> 00:05:43,215
This is not just a detail.

98
00:05:43,215 --> 00:05:45,359
This implies that the turbulence,
for example,

99
00:05:45,359 --> 00:05:49,103
that can develop in the system 
in which the particle trajectories

100
00:05:49,103 --> 00:05:53,811
are much smaller than 
the typical scale length of the system

101
00:05:53,811 --> 00:05:55,238
could be very different.

102
00:05:55,713 --> 00:05:57,944
And of course, last but not the least,

103
00:05:58,110 --> 00:06:01,649
we have a very large 
isotropic population of α's

104
00:06:01,649 --> 00:06:04,634
which will be, again 
by definition of a burning plasma,

105
00:06:04,634 --> 00:06:06,154
the dominant source of heating.

106
00:06:06,404 --> 00:06:09,880
This implies that there will be a coupling
between the profile of the α-power,

107
00:06:09,880 --> 00:06:13,916
the profile of the pressure of the plasma,
the safety factor profile,

108
00:06:13,916 --> 00:06:19,724
the profile of the electric field,
the profile of transport parameters,

109
00:06:19,764 --> 00:06:23,108
the profile of the helium concentration 
and so on and so forth.

110
00:06:23,180 --> 00:06:26,139
So all these elements 
will be coupled in the burning plasma,

111
00:06:26,489 --> 00:06:29,892
whereas in today’s experiments, 
they are completely,

112
00:06:29,892 --> 00:06:32,552
or at least partly,
decoupled from each other.

113
00:06:32,653 --> 00:06:37,493
These are the main elements 
that we need to study

114
00:06:37,493 --> 00:06:39,772
and issues that we need to solve

115
00:06:39,772 --> 00:06:42,826
to get the burning plasma 
and to control it.

116
00:06:42,893 --> 00:06:45,658
First of all, we have to reach 
the burning plasma condition of course,

117
00:06:45,658 --> 00:06:48,526
so we need to identify 
which heating scenarios, for example,

118
00:06:48,526 --> 00:06:52,802
we can have in approaching
the burning plasma conditions.

119
00:06:52,918 --> 00:06:54,912
We need to understand 
what a transport

120
00:06:55,022 --> 00:06:59,049
and turbulence behavior would be like
in these conditions.

121
00:06:59,049 --> 00:07:01,221
In particular 
what would be the effect

122
00:07:01,221 --> 00:07:04,258
of different isotopic masses
in the plasma.

123
00:07:04,350 --> 00:07:07,282
We know that there are differences
in the transport

124
00:07:07,282 --> 00:07:09,519
that we don't fully understand 
between for example

125
00:07:09,519 --> 00:07:11,791
deuterium and tritium plasmas.

126
00:07:12,292 --> 00:07:15,305
We need to learn how to sustain 
the burning conditions.

127
00:07:15,305 --> 00:07:18,021
We need to really make sure
that the self-heating process

128
00:07:18,021 --> 00:07:21,566
is not affected by any major instabilities

129
00:07:21,566 --> 00:07:24,833
or any major problem 
that can rise in the plasma.

130
00:07:26,761 --> 00:07:28,732
Among the problems
that we have to worry about

131
00:07:28,732 --> 00:07:33,538
are the losses of the fast ions
that are of course, those that guarantee

132
00:07:33,538 --> 00:07:35,641
the self-heating process 
in the form of α's

133
00:07:35,641 --> 00:07:37,388
produced by fusion reactions.

134
00:07:38,679 --> 00:07:41,173
We need to see
if the stability of the plasma

135
00:07:41,467 --> 00:07:45,769
is affected by the presence of fast ions
and in which way is it affected.

136
00:07:46,839 --> 00:07:51,006
We also need to have a thought
on the stability of the burn

137
00:07:51,006 --> 00:07:52,626
and how we control it.

138
00:07:52,873 --> 00:07:55,482
Now thinking about the reactor, 
we need to make sure

139
00:07:55,482 --> 00:07:58,751
that the conditions
for the plasma to burn are compatible

140
00:07:58,751 --> 00:08:02,498
with the operation of a reactor 
from which we want to extract energy.

141
00:08:03,707 --> 00:08:06,498
I’m thinking about the interaction
between the plasma and the wall,

142
00:08:06,550 --> 00:08:10,968
the exhaust of power and particles,
how we get rid of the helium ashes,

143
00:08:10,968 --> 00:08:12,645
for example in particular,

144
00:08:12,645 --> 00:08:15,775
helium ashes being 
essentially the α-particles

145
00:08:15,775 --> 00:08:17,755
that have given up their energy
by collisions,

146
00:08:17,755 --> 00:08:21,690
and that we don’t need 
any more in the plasma.

147
00:08:22,756 --> 00:08:25,349
We need to worry about the heat loads,

148
00:08:25,422 --> 00:08:29,913
the high recycling regimes in which 
we have a lot of particles

149
00:08:29,913 --> 00:08:31,453
that are reinjected in the plasma

150
00:08:31,453 --> 00:08:35,160
to the interaction between 
the plasma itself and the walls.

151
00:08:35,576 --> 00:08:38,332
Operating with a large fraction of power

152
00:08:38,332 --> 00:08:42,672
that is radiated out from the plasma.

153
00:08:43,792 --> 00:08:48,417
How we can mitigate disruptions
and other violent events

154
00:08:48,417 --> 00:08:51,488
at the plasma edge,
such as the <i>Edge Localized Modes</i>

155
00:08:51,488 --> 00:08:55,822
that we have investigated briefly
in the previous lecture.

156
00:08:56,626 --> 00:08:59,147
We have to worry about the retention
of tritium in the walls

157
00:08:59,147 --> 00:09:02,624
and avoid or limit the production of dust.

158
00:09:03,380 --> 00:09:06,281
We also need to see
how these phenomena

159
00:09:06,281 --> 00:09:09,911
can be extrapolated 
and what they imply

160
00:09:09,911 --> 00:09:12,019
for the operation of the reactor.

161
00:09:12,246 --> 00:09:14,515
We need to worry
about breeding tritium,

