292
00:17:08,546 --> 00:17:13,280
in that there were no major instabilities,
no major pertubations

293
00:17:13,280 --> 00:17:15,328
to the quiescent plasma.

294
00:17:15,328 --> 00:17:18,102
What we worry about is 
if we have fast ion losses

295
00:17:18,102 --> 00:17:21,658
for different reasons,
then they will influence the power

296
00:17:21,658 --> 00:17:23,897
that will be transferred
from the α's to the electrons

297
00:17:23,897 --> 00:17:25,714
as well as the power 
that will be transferred

298
00:17:25,714 --> 00:17:30,413
from the fast ions issued by collisional,
by additional heating.

299
00:17:30,856 --> 00:17:34,073
In this case power can be transferred
to electrons or to the ions

300
00:17:34,073 --> 00:17:35,877
depending on the energy of the fast ions.

301
00:17:35,979 --> 00:17:39,359
But in all of these cases, 
if fast ion losses are present,

302
00:17:39,359 --> 00:17:41,736
this transfer will be affected 
and therefore,

303
00:17:41,736 --> 00:17:43,759
the plasma will not be heated efficiently.

304
00:17:44,128 --> 00:17:48,725
So what mechanics can we have 
to lose fast ions

305
00:17:48,755 --> 00:17:51,051
in a actual tokamak plasma?

306
00:17:51,103 --> 00:17:54,328
First of all, we worry about
fast ion losses that can happen

307
00:17:54,328 --> 00:17:58,196
because of the 3D nature
of the magnetic fields.

308
00:17:59,760 --> 00:18:03,951
In a practical situation of a tokamak,

309
00:18:04,093 --> 00:18:06,721
the number of coils is of course, finite.

310
00:18:07,234 --> 00:18:11,192
So if I go around the torus
being a charged particle,

311
00:18:11,603 --> 00:18:14,718
I don’t feel a complete 
uniform magnetic field,

312
00:18:14,718 --> 00:18:18,707
I will feel inhomogeneities,
in the intensity of the field.

313
00:18:18,707 --> 00:18:21,612
Just below the coil 
it will be more intense,

314
00:18:21,612 --> 00:18:24,373
in between coils it will be weaker.

315
00:18:25,257 --> 00:18:29,115
And as a charged particle
feels a inhomogeneity magnetic field,

316
00:18:29,115 --> 00:18:31,083
it can be subject to trapping.

317
00:18:31,820 --> 00:18:36,535
And if particles are subject to trapping,
they will not go around the torus,

318
00:18:36,535 --> 00:18:40,762
they will not feel the field
of the tokamak

319
00:18:40,762 --> 00:18:45,045
that we have set up so carefully 
to compensate the various drifts,

320
00:18:45,495 --> 00:18:48,295
and therefore get out 
of the confinement region

321
00:18:48,295 --> 00:18:51,167
being trapped in between coils
and then drifting out

322
00:18:51,167 --> 00:18:52,899
providing direct losses.

323
00:18:53,901 --> 00:18:57,662
These are the so-called <i>ripple losses</i>
because they are caused once more

324
00:18:57,662 --> 00:19:02,535
by the inhomogeneity of the magnetic field
due to the number of coils that’s finite,

325
00:19:03,103 --> 00:19:07,436
which can be simply be called
the ripple of the field,

326
00:19:07,638 --> 00:19:11,128
felt by the fast particles in their
motion around the torus.

327
00:19:11,441 --> 00:19:15,382
This is something that can be
calculated fairly accurately.

328
00:19:15,602 --> 00:19:18,623
An example or remedy 
for a particular scenario ITER

329
00:19:18,623 --> 00:19:20,184
is illustrated here.

330
00:19:20,213 --> 00:19:25,753
One can actually insert ferritic materials
so high µ material

331
00:19:25,753 --> 00:19:30,142
to smooth out these variations
and reduce losses significantly.

332
00:19:30,168 --> 00:19:33,482
This kind of solution
is already foreseen for ITER,

333
00:19:33,482 --> 00:19:35,782
even considered 
for the steps after ITER

334
00:19:35,782 --> 00:19:39,092
but there is still a few open issues
that one needs to address.

335
00:19:39,728 --> 00:19:42,016
One of them is the effect 
of the blanket modules

336
00:19:42,016 --> 00:19:45,083
which contain ferromagnetic material,
therefore possible perturbations

337
00:19:45,083 --> 00:19:46,975
to the field structure.

338
00:19:46,975 --> 00:19:49,915
Blanket module are 
of course necessary for tritium breeding.

339
00:19:50,573 --> 00:19:53,251
Fast ion losses can also happen
because of low frequency

340
00:19:53,251 --> 00:19:55,623
magnetohydrodynamics modes.

341
00:19:55,623 --> 00:19:57,381
There are many modes that are possible.

342
00:19:57,381 --> 00:19:59,535
We illustrate a couple of examples.

343
00:19:59,535 --> 00:20:02,282
In general, different kinds of resonances
can be associated

344
00:20:02,282 --> 00:20:04,775
with the complex particle orbits

345
00:20:04,775 --> 00:20:07,677
and lead to different possible
interactions.

346
00:20:09,088 --> 00:20:13,615
This image that we have seen 
in previous parts of the course,

347
00:20:13,634 --> 00:20:17,278
illustrates the complexity
of the orbits in a tokamak,

348
00:20:17,278 --> 00:20:19,853
for ions, for example.

349
00:20:20,365 --> 00:20:23,346
Of course you have the
fast gyromotion around a field lines

350
00:20:23,346 --> 00:20:26,459
which is associated 
with the cyclotron frequency,

351
00:20:26,459 --> 00:20:27,678
and that’s one resonance.

352
00:20:27,678 --> 00:20:31,486
But now we consider 
much smaller frequencies,

353
00:20:31,486 --> 00:20:33,278
much slower time scales.

354
00:20:33,278 --> 00:20:38,654
Now we have seen already 
that the motion of the ions

355
00:20:38,654 --> 00:20:41,175
around the tokamak
is actually characterized

356
00:20:41,175 --> 00:20:43,331
by what we call <i>banana orbits</i>

357
00:20:43,419 --> 00:20:46,573
which are orbits that are produced

358
00:20:46,573 --> 00:20:51,393
by the fact that the particles feel 
regions of different strengths

359
00:20:51,393 --> 00:20:54,451
in a magnetic field
and therefore are trapped.

360
00:20:55,269 --> 00:21:00,197
And the turning points
of this trapping motion are related

361
00:21:00,197 --> 00:21:02,671
to the in-out asymmetry of the field.

362
00:21:03,755 --> 00:21:06,802
If we project these orbits
on a poloidal plane,

363
00:21:06,802 --> 00:21:10,406
they look like bananas
so we refer to them as banana orbits.

364
00:21:10,965 --> 00:21:14,466
And if we look at the motion 
of the particles along these orbits,

365
00:21:14,466 --> 00:21:18,066
if we see again in the poloidal plane,
the particles will go around.

366
00:21:18,066 --> 00:21:25,067
So there will be a frequency associated
with this motion around the banana orbit.

367
00:21:25,230 --> 00:21:29,875
And that’s one of the frequencies
that we can have coinciding

368
00:21:29,875 --> 00:21:32,711
with the frequency of an instability.

369
00:21:32,711 --> 00:21:35,533
And of course, when the frequency 
of a motion of a particle coincides

370
00:21:35,533 --> 00:21:37,021
with the frequency of an instability,

371
00:21:37,021 --> 00:21:39,549
you can have a very efficient exchange
of energy momentum.

372
00:21:39,549 --> 00:21:42,220
You can have very efficient drive 
of an MHD instability.

373
00:21:43,032 --> 00:21:46,652
Another example
is that of the so-called precession

374
00:21:46,652 --> 00:21:49,371
or <i>drift precession</i> of the banana orbits.

375
00:21:49,655 --> 00:21:53,086
For that let’s illustrate it 
with a plot from the top.

376
00:21:53,086 --> 00:21:55,028
This is a top view of a tokamak

377
00:21:55,028 --> 00:21:59,025
we have seen that the particle orbits
can be trapped

378
00:21:59,025 --> 00:22:03,901
and therefore not complete
a full toroidal circumference.

379
00:22:04,013 --> 00:22:07,708
But in fact there is
some asymmetry between the -

380
00:22:08,298 --> 00:22:12,944
if you like the trajectory forward
and the return of the trajectory,

381
00:22:13,042 --> 00:22:17,858
so that this orbit will slowly drift

382
00:22:17,898 --> 00:22:20,138
in one particular toroidal direction.

383
00:22:20,726 --> 00:22:26,327
It is as if the banana orbit 
would go in fact, around the torus,

384
00:22:26,767 --> 00:22:28,183
seen from the top.

385
00:22:28,287 --> 00:22:33,128
And the frequency associated with
that is a so-called <i>precession frequency</i>.

386
00:22:33,302 --> 00:22:38,151
That is slower than the frequency
associated with the motion of the particle

387
00:22:38,151 --> 00:22:42,506
along the banana orbit itself which
is referred to as the <i>bounce frequency.</i>

388
00:22:42,971 --> 00:22:49,030
So we have, just using these two examples,
two possible frequencies

389
00:22:49,030 --> 00:22:51,564
for possible resonances 
with plasma instabilities.

390
00:22:51,564 --> 00:22:56,497
The precession frequency 
of the particle drift around the torus

391
00:22:56,497 --> 00:23:00,415
and the bounce frequency of the particle
around the banana orbit.

392
00:23:01,556 --> 00:23:03,776
Both of these frequencies
are much, much smaller

393
00:23:03,776 --> 00:23:06,826
than the cyclotron frequency and,
therefore, can lead to resonances

394
00:23:06,826 --> 00:23:11,534
with low frequency global modes
of the MHD kind.

395
00:23:12,438 --> 00:23:16,681
And I’d like to take two examples
for two of these modes.

396
00:23:16,710 --> 00:23:19,529
The first one is the so-called
<i>fishbone instability</i>.

397
00:23:20,103 --> 00:23:24,058
It’s a name that was given historically
because the signal

398
00:23:24,058 --> 00:23:26,850
associated with the perturbation 
that was observed in a plasma,

399
00:23:26,924 --> 00:23:31,246
would have a character of bursts going up.

400
00:23:31,246 --> 00:23:35,652
For example in the perturbed
