461
00:27:09,564 --> 00:27:13,471
These large orbits are expected
to average out the effect of turbulence.

462
00:27:14,057 --> 00:27:17,969
And this plot we illustrate
that phenomenon.

463
00:27:17,969 --> 00:27:21,220
So if you have a thermal ion
which has a very small orbit,

464
00:27:21,220 --> 00:27:25,881
it will be influenced 
by the electric field of the turbulence

465
00:27:25,881 --> 00:27:27,384
in one particular direction.

466
00:27:27,384 --> 00:27:29,391
It will receive a kick
in one particular direction

467
00:27:29,391 --> 00:27:33,275
and it will be therefore affected
in its confinement and its transport.

468
00:27:34,198 --> 00:27:37,423
As I increase the size
of the orbit of the ion

469
00:27:37,423 --> 00:27:40,312
by increasing typically its energy,

470
00:27:41,008 --> 00:27:45,470
I increase the number of turbulent eddies
or turbulent structures,

471
00:27:45,470 --> 00:27:48,497
that the fast ion interacts
with over one orbit

472
00:27:48,497 --> 00:27:51,744
and therefore, receiving kicks 
in different directions along one orbit.

473
00:27:52,354 --> 00:27:54,936
These kicks will therefore be averaged out

474
00:27:55,046 --> 00:27:57,627
and the net effect 
will be reduced to zero.

475
00:27:58,370 --> 00:28:02,849
The key paremeter in this orbit
averaging effect is the ratio

476
00:28:02,849 --> 00:28:06,050
between the fast ion energy
and the background plasma temperature.

477
00:28:06,132 --> 00:28:10,342
In a sense this ratio is a proxy
for the ratio

478
00:28:10,342 --> 00:28:13,735
between the size of the ion’s orbits

479
00:28:14,313 --> 00:28:17,448
and the size 
of the turbulent structures.

480
00:28:17,983 --> 00:28:22,000
The second parameter that of course
influences this interaction,

481
00:28:22,000 --> 00:28:25,865
is how long do fast ions
remain fast in a plasma,

482
00:28:25,865 --> 00:28:28,768
that is the slowing down time.

483
00:28:28,768 --> 00:28:33,629
Now I said before that in this case
we would rather find good piece of news,

484
00:28:33,629 --> 00:28:38,620
because if we do the estimates for ITER
and future reactors,

485
00:28:39,180 --> 00:28:44,246
we find out that the value
of this ratio of Efast/T

486
00:28:44,246 --> 00:28:45,799
should be large enough

487
00:28:45,799 --> 00:28:48,460
that the turbulence
effects on the NBI ions

488
00:28:48,460 --> 00:28:53,022
and even more importantly, 
on the α's, should be negligible.

489
00:28:53,690 --> 00:28:57,626
I now turn to the last mechanism
of fast ion losses I'd like to discuss,

490
00:28:57,626 --> 00:29:03,097
that is due to the interaction
with Alfvén waves.

491
00:29:04,007 --> 00:29:09,226
So as we said, the α-particles
are born at 3.5 MeV.

492
00:29:09,322 --> 00:29:10,972
They would slow down collisionally,

493
00:29:10,972 --> 00:29:13,627
first on electrons 
then eventually on ions.

494
00:29:13,737 --> 00:29:16,949
And during that slowing down
which lasts a microscopic time,

495
00:29:17,016 --> 00:29:18,686
of the order of a second,

496
00:29:18,686 --> 00:29:21,633
they can encounter
a wave-particle resonance.

497
00:29:22,023 --> 00:29:27,165
So they can drive efficiently
an instability in the form

498
00:29:27,165 --> 00:29:30,662
for example of an Alfven wave,
- as we will see in a moment,

499
00:29:31,811 --> 00:29:34,701
which in turn - if it grows
to large amplitudes,

500
00:29:35,132 --> 00:29:36,843
could give rise to losses.

501
00:29:38,028 --> 00:29:42,156
The losses of the fast ions,
in this case of the α's,

502
00:29:42,156 --> 00:29:46,370
would of course prevent
an efficient transfer of that energy

503
00:29:46,370 --> 00:29:48,353
to the background plasma.

504
00:29:49,348 --> 00:29:53,517
We have studied Alfvén waves
in previous lectures.

505
00:29:53,517 --> 00:29:58,425
I'd just like to remind ourselves
that they come from the following

506
00:29:58,425 --> 00:29:59,992
very simple mechanism.

507
00:29:59,992 --> 00:30:02,309
The B-field and the plasma
are frozen together

508
00:30:02,309 --> 00:30:04,351
in the frame of ideal MHD.

509
00:30:04,351 --> 00:30:09,040
So we can see the field lines
as strings subject to tension

510
00:30:09,040 --> 00:30:11,981
and subject to the interaction
with the plasma inertia.

511
00:30:12,093 --> 00:30:14,288
The combination of tension
and the plasma inertia

512
00:30:14,390 --> 00:30:16,473
gives the propagation of Alfvén waves.

513
00:30:16,473 --> 00:30:18,768
Let me just sketch that in a simple way.

514
00:30:18,768 --> 00:30:23,252
Say we bend the field lines, 
-these are supposed to be field lines,

515
00:30:23,252 --> 00:30:26,012
because there is a perturbation
[δB_wave] of the magnetic field,

516
00:30:26,838 --> 00:30:30,223
due to a perturbation of the velocity
of the plasma [δv_wave].

517
00:30:30,223 --> 00:30:33,245
So the unperturbed magnetic field
is in this direction

518
00:30:33,426 --> 00:30:36,111
and we locally have a perturbation
of this kind.

519
00:30:37,758 --> 00:30:42,782
This combination of tension
and inertia in MHD,

520
00:30:43,548 --> 00:30:49,618
is such that we have a wave 
that will propagate

521
00:30:49,618 --> 00:30:52,529
in the direction parallel
to the magnetic field,

522
00:30:52,529 --> 00:30:55,154
with a phase velocity 
that will be the Alfvén speed

523
00:30:55,154 --> 00:30:59,268
that will be related to the intensity
of the field divided by

524
00:30:59,268 --> 00:31:01,979
the square root 
of the plasma mass density

525
00:31:02,044 --> 00:31:04,926
which is a measure for the inertia 
that is involved in

526
00:31:04,926 --> 00:31:07,746
the mechanism 
for the propagation of the wave.

527
00:31:09,898 --> 00:31:11,774
So you see the slowing down α's,

528
00:31:12,347 --> 00:31:14,968
or for that matter fast ions 
from NBI or even ICRH,

529
00:31:14,968 --> 00:31:16,826
can actually resonate 
with Alfvén waves

530
00:31:16,826 --> 00:31:21,609
and therefore, drive them unstable
giving energy to them.

531
00:31:22,572 --> 00:31:25,852
Why is this resonance almost inevitable?

532
00:31:25,982 --> 00:31:32,003
The reason for that is that if I draw
the distribution function for the α's,

533
00:31:32,003 --> 00:31:36,425
as a function of time 
and as a function of their velocity,

534
00:31:36,560 --> 00:31:39,185
normalized to the birth velocity.

535
00:31:39,303 --> 00:31:43,830
The birth velocity corresponds
to the 3.5 MeV of energy.

536
00:31:43,888 --> 00:31:49,873
Say this is 1, .2, .4, .6, .8.

537
00:31:50,053 --> 00:31:52,271
We have something
that is a function of time,

538
00:31:52,322 --> 00:31:58,032
so initially the α-particles 
will be generated at the birth velocity

539
00:31:58,032 --> 00:31:59,758
corresponding to their birth energy.

540
00:31:59,758 --> 00:32:03,682
And then they will 
progressively slow down.

541
00:32:03,682 --> 00:32:10,308
So if this was t₀,
this is now t₁, t₂, t₃, t₄,

542
00:32:10,308 --> 00:32:13,251
and t₅.

543
00:32:14,054 --> 00:32:15,675
During this slowing down,

544
00:32:16,314 --> 00:32:20,494
the Alfvén velocity will be encountered

545
00:32:20,494 --> 00:32:24,505
because the Alfvén velocity 
or Alfvén speed

546
00:32:24,505 --> 00:32:29,925
is typically just below
the birth velocity.

547
00:32:30,820 --> 00:32:33,084
So there’s no way
we can avoid that resonance.

548
00:32:33,084 --> 00:32:37,774
And that’s for typical parameters 
corresponding to a few teslas device,

549
00:32:37,774 --> 00:32:43,016
10 to 15 KeV of temperature
and 10²⁰/m³ of density.

550
00:32:43,365 --> 00:32:48,661
The other point is that there will be a
potential for a very effective interaction

551
00:32:48,661 --> 00:32:53,309
between the slowing down α's
and the Afvén wave

552
00:32:53,458 --> 00:32:58,641
corresponding to this range
of velocity values.

553
00:32:59,132 --> 00:33:04,597
Because the thermal speed
for the bulk ions

554
00:33:04,626 --> 00:33:06,737
is much, much smaller.

555
00:33:07,302 --> 00:33:12,769
For example, for deuterium and tritium,

556
00:33:13,310 --> 00:33:16,696
there will be something 
around this region.

557
00:33:16,838 --> 00:33:21,618
Tritium’s a little lower
and deuterium a little higher.

558
00:33:22,118 --> 00:33:24,213
So there’s a long way
for the α's to slow down

559
00:33:24,213 --> 00:33:29,179
before they reach the thermal
speed of deuterons and tritons,

560
00:33:29,270 --> 00:33:32,800
and during that long way, 
they have also long time

561
00:33:32,800 --> 00:33:36,457
to interact with the Alfvén waves
with which they will become resonant.

562
00:33:37,459 --> 00:33:40,458
So when is the wave driven unstable?

563
00:33:40,588 --> 00:33:45,016
Well we have a free energy source
which is the gradient in the pressure

564
00:33:45,116 --> 00:33:48,855
of the α-particles 
and if that is sufficiently high,

565
00:33:49,030 --> 00:33:50,357
there will be a drive,

566
00:33:50,357 --> 00:33:55,346
and of course if this drive
will be exceeding

567
00:33:55,346 --> 00:33:57,398
the background plasma damping.

568
00:33:57,398 --> 00:34:01,478
It will be provided by 
a number of mechanisms in the plasma.

569
00:34:01,554 --> 00:34:05,032
Now we have seen
what Alfvén waves look like in general

570
00:34:05,032 --> 00:34:06,920
and what their physical mechanisms is,

571
00:34:06,982 --> 00:34:09,567
without going to too many complications,

572
00:34:09,567 --> 00:34:13,762
we noticed that in a tokamak,
the geometry of the field

573
00:34:13,762 --> 00:34:17,492
is such that the dispersion is modified
and in fact, is much more complex.

574
00:34:17,492 --> 00:34:20,482
But the point is that the dispersion
of Alfvén waves in a tokamak

575
00:34:20,482 --> 00:34:23,420
still allows for very weakly damped
global modes

576
00:34:23,420 --> 00:34:26,067
we refer to as <i>Alfvén Eigenmodes</i>.

577
00:34:26,806 --> 00:34:32,769
In fact, it is one of the most striking 
successes of MHD theory,

578
00:34:32,978 --> 00:34:34,551
to predict the existence 
of these modes

579
00:34:34,624 --> 00:34:37,673
and to even predict
some of the main features.

580
00:34:37,703 --> 00:34:41,691
Features that have been observed 
experimentally and quite accurately.

581
00:34:42,595 --> 00:34:44,221
An example is shown here:

582
00:34:44,984 --> 00:34:48,168
this is a structure that’s calculated 
for an Alfvén Eigenmode

583
00:34:50,616 --> 00:34:55,292
in which we have inserted
in some portions,

584
00:34:56,013 --> 00:35:01,612
data corresponding to measurements
of the same Alfvén Eigenmode.

585
00:35:01,679 --> 00:35:06,094
In this case data taken
using electron cyclotron emission imaging.

586
00:35:06,902 --> 00:35:09,823
You can hardly notice the difference
between the data

587
00:35:10,341 --> 00:35:11,986
and the theory prediction.

588
00:35:12,909 --> 00:35:14,892
So the modes are there.

589
00:35:14,892 --> 00:35:18,908
The modes follow,
at least in their main feature,

590
00:35:18,908 --> 00:35:20,387
the theory predictions.

591
00:35:20,895 --> 00:35:25,386
Do they also cause losses
as we fear they would?

592
00:35:25,880 --> 00:35:29,309
The answer is:
in many circumstances, they do.

593
00:35:29,879 --> 00:35:32,205
Losses and redistribution
due to Alfvén waves

594
00:35:32,205 --> 00:35:34,080
have been seen in many experiments.

595
00:35:34,638 --> 00:35:37,312
In this plot compiled by a Rich Hawryluk

596
00:35:37,312 --> 00:35:42,824
from data from TFTR, 
we see that the fraction of losses here

597
00:35:42,824 --> 00:35:46,874
is plotted as a function
of the input power.

598
00:35:47,813 --> 00:35:50,063
On the other side of the plot

599
00:35:50,063 --> 00:35:52,399
the other axis corresponds
to the mode amplitude.

600
00:35:52,496 --> 00:35:56,928
Of course the larger, the more amplitude,
the larger the fractional losses.

601
00:35:56,990 --> 00:36:02,235
We see that for both NBI driven 
Alfvén Eigenmodes

602
00:36:02,235 --> 00:36:07,685
or ICRF driven Alfvén Eigenmodes,
we can have significant levels of losses.

603
00:36:07,825 --> 00:36:10,177
In DT experiments,

604
00:36:10,235 --> 00:36:13,031
very weakly Alfvén Eigenmodes
were observed

605
00:36:13,037 --> 00:36:15,554
and so no significant losses 
were observed but

606
00:36:15,554 --> 00:36:17,536
that doesn’t mean 
we should not worry about them

607
00:36:17,536 --> 00:36:20,947
in the future, because 
it was really corresponding

608
00:36:20,947 --> 00:36:25,447
to a very small input power in the drive,
in that case in the α drive,

609
00:36:25,506 --> 00:36:30,463
and therefore, to a very small mode
amplitude range for these modes.

610
00:36:32,267 --> 00:36:36,657
In fact we have to worry
about loss and redistribution

611
00:36:36,657 --> 00:36:39,757
because in ITER and in the future reactor
we can only withstand

612
00:36:39,757 --> 00:36:41,579
a few percent of α losses.

613
00:36:42,367 --> 00:36:45,154
There is therefore
an ongoing research to investigate

614
00:36:45,154 --> 00:36:49,109
the linear stability of the modes, 
when are they present at all,

615
00:36:49,149 --> 00:36:52,803
-which results from the balance 
between the drive to the fast particles,

616
00:36:52,819 --> 00:36:55,498
and the damping
from the background plasma,

617
00:36:55,498 --> 00:37:00,049
and to also see how the modes
evolve non-linearly and what is the link

618
00:37:00,049 --> 00:37:03,503
between the wave property 
and the redistribution

619
00:37:03,503 --> 00:37:05,701
and the losses that the waves cause.

620
00:37:05,738 --> 00:37:10,882
Just to give you one example
of this kind of investigations,

621
00:37:10,882 --> 00:37:16,248
this is what we studied on the JET tokamak
in terms of the linear stability.

622
00:37:16,248 --> 00:37:19,231
The idea here is that
the linear stability mode is investigated

623
00:37:19,231 --> 00:37:22,779
using antennas, these are 
the four antennas

624
00:37:22,779 --> 00:37:25,528
installed inside the JET vessel
that launch

625
00:37:25,528 --> 00:37:29,441
low amplitude stable modes
in the plasma.

626
00:37:30,734 --> 00:37:35,409
The frequency of the antenna
is swept and the eigenmode appears

627
00:37:35,409 --> 00:37:38,962
as a resonance in the plasma
response to that antenna signal.

628
00:37:39,979 --> 00:37:43,180
And this is a driven mode
so its frequency of course

629
00:37:43,180 --> 00:37:46,783
corresponds to the peak
of this resonant response.

630
00:37:46,783 --> 00:37:51,097
In simple terms, 
the width of the resonant response

631
00:37:51,097 --> 00:37:53,076
is actually the damping rate of the mode.

632
00:37:53,121 --> 00:37:58,072
So one can drive these modes
and even track them in real time.

633
00:37:58,072 --> 00:38:00,498
So drive them one after the other
as the plasma evolves

634
00:38:00,498 --> 00:38:04,662
and extract their width in real time.

635
00:38:04,662 --> 00:38:09,454
The measurement that is 
of the damping rate for the mode

636
00:38:09,454 --> 00:38:11,850
that would be present 
in the burning plasma.

637
00:38:12,602 --> 00:38:15,703
Finally, I would like to say a few words
about the stability of the burn

638
00:38:15,703 --> 00:38:17,752
and its possible control.

639
00:38:18,488 --> 00:38:21,846
We want to achieve 
a burning plasma regime

640
00:38:21,846 --> 00:38:26,068
that sustains without 
- any major macro-instabilities,

641
00:38:26,137 --> 00:38:29,857
- any significant fast ion losses, 
- any disruptions,

642
00:38:29,857 --> 00:38:32,130
and 
- any build-up of the helium ashes.

643
00:38:33,459 --> 00:38:40,394
In principle, a thermal runaway
can occur at high fusion gain.

644
00:38:40,506 --> 00:38:45,570
This is represented in this plot 
where the input power is represented

645
00:38:45,570 --> 00:38:49,184
as a function of density and temperature,

646
00:38:49,514 --> 00:38:52,687
to achieve a certain level
of fusion power

647
00:38:52,771 --> 00:38:56,613
and we can see that the input power
could go to zero

648
00:38:56,613 --> 00:38:58,494
in particular regions of this plot,

649
00:38:58,494 --> 00:39:02,222
which means that we would have
a runaway towards ignition,

650
00:39:02,222 --> 00:39:04,170
which we don’t necessarily want.

651
00:39:04,170 --> 00:39:07,027
We will lose control of the plasma burn.

652
00:39:07,027 --> 00:39:09,828
As we will see in an exercise, however,

653
00:39:10,389 --> 00:39:13,632
we have a confinement degradation
with power.

654
00:39:13,685 --> 00:39:17,251
Which means that the burn, 
in fact, should be globally stable.

655
00:39:17,519 --> 00:39:20,409
To control the burn, 
we have a number of possible actuators,

656
00:39:20,409 --> 00:39:24,568
although, as we said, the plasma 
is really a self-organized system

657
00:39:24,568 --> 00:39:28,219
when we have the burning plant regime.

658
00:39:28,219 --> 00:39:32,131
We can nevertheless try to act 
on the heating power,

659
00:39:32,240 --> 00:39:37,931
on fueling of the core, on the DT mix,

660
00:39:38,011 --> 00:39:40,831
on impurities that we have in the plasma,

661
00:39:40,831 --> 00:39:45,571
and we can, in fact, even manipulate
the fast ion phase space distribution

662
00:39:45,571 --> 00:39:47,318
to optimize our burn.

663
00:39:47,724 --> 00:39:50,782
So in summary we have seen together
the burning plasmas are characterized

664
00:39:50,782 --> 00:39:54,442
by the interplay of plasma dynamics
and external systems.

665
00:39:55,025 --> 00:39:57,975
The core of the plasma
is a complex self-organized system

666
00:39:58,337 --> 00:40:02,012
on which we can have
a small amount of control.

667
00:40:03,280 --> 00:40:05,552
In today’s experiment 
we can achieve some progress

668
00:40:05,552 --> 00:40:08,461
on seperate building blocks
for the burning regime.

669
00:40:08,461 --> 00:40:11,332
But the coupling of all of these elements
makes extrapolations

670
00:40:11,332 --> 00:40:14,542
from the weakly self-heated plasma
we have today very difficult

671
00:40:14,542 --> 00:40:16,726
and may lead to new phenomena.

672
00:40:16,726 --> 00:40:20,763
And that’s why we need to build
an experiment that runs a plasma

673
00:40:20,763 --> 00:40:21,973
in a burning regime.

674
00:40:21,973 --> 00:40:23,970
This is what we will discuss
in the next lecture.

675
00:40:23,970 --> 00:40:25,390
And that is ITER.
